# Safety denylist — TEMPLATE (this .example file is PUBLIC)
#
# Copy this file to `.safety-denylist` (which is gitignored) and fill in the
# REAL sensitive terms. The publishing checklist scan commands read the real
# `.safety-denylist`, never this template, so the actual values never land in
# git history.
#
# Format: one term per line. Blank lines and lines starting with `#` are
# ignored. Terms are matched case-insensitively as fixed strings (grep -F -i).
# Keep terms specific enough to avoid false positives but broad enough to catch
# variants (e.g. include a name both with and without spacing if relevant).
#
# Put the real values in .safety-denylist locally. Examples of what belongs:

# --- Employer / work identity ---
ExampleCorp
example-corp-internal
acme-platform-team

# --- Real personal identities ---
Firstname
Lastname
Firstname Lastname
personal-folder-name

# --- Network / infrastructure identifiers ---
your-tailnet-name.ts.net
your-tailnet-name

# --- Private repo names that must not appear publicly ---
private-work-repo-a
private-work-repo-b

# --- Personal / employer email addresses ---
you@example.com
you@employer.example
